comment.body:
The `useSupabaseClient` function has a generic type parameter, so you can pass your database types in there.

```ts
export interface Database {
  public: {
    Tables: {
      blog: {
        Row: {
          id: string
          info: Json | null
          topics: string[] | null
        }
        Insert: {
          id: string
          info?: Json | null
          topics?: string[] | null
        }
        Update: {
          id?: string
          info?: Json | null
          topics?: string[] | null
        }
      }
}
```

You can actually use the [supabase-cli](https://github.com/supabase/cli) to generate types for your entire schema.

Install the supabase-cli, link your project using `supabase link` and then generate the types using `supabase gen types typescript --linked > lib/database.types.ts`. Now, you can import the `Database` interface from the generated `database.types.ts`.

```ts
const supabaseClient = useSupabaseClient<Database>()

// This it typed now
const blogs = await supabaseClient.from('blog').select('*')
```

